## Explore: Why Inverse Trigonometric Functions Exist

Since trigonometric functions are not one-to-one (they repeat values), inverse functions must have restricted domains to be well-defined. The ranges are chosen to give one principal value for each input.

Inquiry Question:
Why do inverse sine, cosine, and tangent have different restricted ranges, and how do these ranges affect the values you get when solving equations?

